h2\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Thread.EndCriticalRegion%2A&gt;</ph> to identify lock regions.","pos":[12581,12732],"source":" Use the methods <xref:System.Threading.Thread.BeginCriticalRegion%2A> and <xref:System.Threading.Thread.EndCriticalRegion%2A> to identify lock regions."},{"content":"They are static methods on the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Thread&gt;</ph> class that only apply to the current thread, helping to prevent one thread from editing another thread’s lock count.","pos":[12734,12912],"source":"  They are static methods on the <xref:System.Threading.Thread> class that only apply to the current thread, helping to prevent one thread from editing another thread’s lock count."},{"pos":[12919,13201],"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Monitor.Enter%2A&gt;</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Monitor.Exit%2A&gt;</ph> have this CLR notification built in, so their usage is recommended as well as the use of the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>lock Statement<ept id=\"p1\">](~/docs/csharp/language-reference/keywords/lock-statement.md)</ept>, which uses these methods.","source":"<xref:System.Threading.Monitor.Enter%2A> and <xref:System.Threading.Monitor.Exit%2A> have this CLR notification built in, so their usage is recommended as well as the use of the [lock Statement](~/docs/csharp/language-reference/keywords/lock-statement.md), which uses these methods."},{"content":"Other locking mechanisms such as spin locks and <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.AutoResetEvent&gt;</ph> must call these methods to notify the CLR that a critical section is being entered.","pos":[13208,13378],"source":"Other locking mechanisms such as spin locks and <xref:System.Threading.AutoResetEvent> must call these methods to notify the CLR that a critical section is being entered."},{"content":"These methods do not take any locks; they inform the CLR that code is executing in a critical section and aborting the thread could leave shared state inconsistent.","pos":[13380,13544]},{"content":"If you have defined your own lock type, such as a custom <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.ReaderWriterLock&gt;</ph> class, use these lock count methods.","pos":[13546,13680],"source":"  If you have defined your own lock type, such as a custom <xref:System.Threading.ReaderWriterLock> class, use these lock count methods."},{"pos":[13691,13709],"content":"Code Analysis Rule","linkify":"Code Analysis Rule","nodes":[{"content":"Code Analysis Rule","pos":[0,18]}]},{"content":"Mark and identify all locks using <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Thread.BeginCriticalRegion%2A&gt;</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Thread.EndCriticalRegion%2A&gt;</ph>.","pos":[13713,13857],"source":"Mark and identify all locks using <xref:System.Threading.Thread.BeginCriticalRegion%2A> and <xref:System.Threading.Thread.EndCriticalRegion%2A>."},{"content":"Do not use <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Interlocked.CompareExchange%2A&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Interlocked.Increment%2A&gt;</ph>, and <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Interlocked.Decrement%2A&gt;</ph> in a loop.","pos":[13858,14038],"source":" Do not use <xref:System.Threading.Interlocked.CompareExchange%2A>, <xref:System.Threading.Interlocked.Increment%2A>, and <xref:System.Threading.Interlocked.Decrement%2A> in a loop."},{"content":"Do not do a platform invoke of the Win32 variants of these methods.","pos":[14040,14107]},{"content":"Do not use <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Thread.Sleep%2A&gt;</ph> in a loop.","pos":[14109,14170],"source":"  Do not use <xref:System.Threading.Thread.Sleep%2A> in a loop."},{"content":"Do not use volatile fields.","pos":[14172,14199]},{"pos":[14209,14282],"content":"Cleanup Code Must Be in a finally or a catch Block, Not Following a catch","linkify":"Cleanup Code Must Be in a finally or a catch Block, Not Following a catch","nodes":[{"content":"Cleanup Code Must Be in a finally or a catch Block, Not Following a catch","pos":[0,73]}]},{"content":"Cleanup code should never follow a <ph id=\"ph1\">`catch`</ph> block; it should be in a <ph id=\"ph2\">`finally`</ph> or in the <ph id=\"ph3\">`catch`</ph> block itself.","pos":[14286,14395],"source":"Cleanup code should never follow a `catch` block; it should be in a `finally` or in the `catch` block itself."},{"content":"This should be a normal good practice.","pos":[14397,14435]},{"content":"A <ph id=\"ph1\">`finally`</ph> block is generally preferred because it runs the same code both when an exception is thrown and when the end of the <ph id=\"ph2\">`try`</ph> block is normally encountered.","pos":[14437,14601],"source":"  A `finally` block is generally preferred because it runs the same code both when an exception is thrown and when the end of the `try` block is normally encountered."},{"content":"In the event of an unexpected exception being thrown, for example a <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.ThreadAbortException&gt;</ph>, the cleanup code will not run.","pos":[14603,14747],"source":"  In the event of an unexpected exception being thrown, for example a <xref:System.Threading.ThreadAbortException>, the cleanup code will not run."},{"content":"Any unmanaged resources that you would clean up in a <ph id=\"ph1\">`finally`</ph> should ideally be wrapped in a <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle&gt;</ph> to prevent leaks.","pos":[14749,14909],"source":"  Any unmanaged resources that you would clean up in a `finally` should ideally be wrapped in a <xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle> to prevent leaks."},{"content":"Note the C# <ph id=\"ph1\">`using`</ph> keyword can be used effectively to dispose of objects, including handles.","pos":[14911,15004],"source":"  Note the C# `using` keyword can be used effectively to dispose of objects, including handles."},{"content":"Although <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.AppDomain&gt;</ph> recycling can clean up resources on the finalizer thread, it is still important to put cleanup code in the correct place.","pos":[15011,15165],"source":"Although <xref:System.AppDomain> recycling can clean up resources on the finalizer thread, it is still important to put cleanup code in the correct place."},{"content":"Note that if a thread receives an asynchronous exception without holding a lock, the CLR attempts to end the thread itself without having to recycle the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.AppDomain&gt;</ph>.","pos":[15167,15344],"source":"  Note that if a thread receives an asynchronous exception without holding a lock, the CLR attempts to end the thread itself without having to recycle the <xref:System.AppDomain>."},{"content":"Ensuring that resources are cleaned up sooner rather than later helps by making more resources available, and by better managing the lifetime.","pos":[15346,15488]},{"content":"If you do not explicitly close a handle to a file in some error code path then wait for the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle&gt;</ph> finalizer to clean it up, the next time your code runs it may fail trying to access the exact same file if the finalizer has not already run.","pos":[15490,15772],"source":"  If you do not explicitly close a handle to a file in some error code path then wait for the <xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle> finalizer to clean it up, the next time your code runs it may fail trying to access the exact same file if the finalizer has not already run."},{"content":"For this reason, ensuring that cleanup code exists and works correctly will help recover from failures more cleanly and quickly, even though it is not strictly necessary.","pos":[15774,15944]},{"pos":[15955,15973],"content":"Code Analysis Rule","linkify":"Code Analysis Rule","nodes":[{"content":"Code Analysis Rule","pos":[0,18]}]},{"content":"Cleanup code after <ph id=\"ph1\">`catch`</ph> needs to be in a <ph id=\"ph2\">`finally`</ph> block.","pos":[15977,16037],"source":"Cleanup code after `catch` needs to be in a `finally` block."},{"content":"Place calls to dispose in a finally block.","pos":[16038,16080]},{"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">`catch`</ph> blocks should end in a throw or rethrow.","pos":[16082,16130],"source":"`catch` blocks should end in a throw or rethrow."},{"content":"While there will be exceptions, such as code detecting whether a network connection can be established where you might get any of a large number of exceptions, any code that requires the catching of a number of exceptions under normal circumstances should give an indication that the code should be tested to see if it will succeed.","pos":[16132,16464]},{"pos":[16474,16594],"content":"Process-Wide Mutable Shared State Between Application Domains Should Be Eliminated or Use a Constrained Execution Region","linkify":"Process-Wide Mutable Shared State Between Application Domains Should Be Eliminated or Use a Constrained Execution Region","nodes":[{"content":"Process-Wide Mutable Shared State Between Application Domains Should Be Eliminated or Use a Constrained Execution Region","pos":[0,120]}]},{"content":"As described in the introduction, it can be very difficult to write managed code that monitors process-wide shared state across application domains in a reliable manner.","pos":[16598,16767]},{"content":"Process-wide shared state is any sort of data structure shared between application domains, either in Win32 code, inside the CLR, or in managed code using remoting.","pos":[16769,16933]},{"content":"Any mutable shared state is very difficult to correctly write in managed code, and any static shared state might be done only with great care.","pos":[16935,17077]},{"content":"If you have process-wide or machine-wide shared state, find some way to eliminate it or protect the shared state using a constrained execution region (CER).","pos":[17079,17235]},{"content":"Note that any library with shared state that is not identified and corrected could caus