ref:System.Type> instance takes a lock that affects the entire process, not just the <xref:System.AppDomain>."},{"content":"If one <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.AppDomain&gt;</ph> takes a lock on a <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Type&gt;</ph> object then that thread gets abruptly aborted, it will not release the lock.","pos":[19999,20143],"source":"  If one <xref:System.AppDomain> takes a lock on a <xref:System.Type> object then that thread gets abruptly aborted, it will not release the lock."},{"content":"This lock then may cause other application domains to deadlock.","pos":[20145,20208]},{"content":"A good way to take locks in static methods involves adding a static internal synchronization object to the code.","pos":[20215,20327]},{"content":"This could be initialized in the class constructor if one is present, but if not it can be initialized like this:","pos":[20329,20442]},{"content":"Then when taking a lock, use the <ph id=\"ph1\">`InternalSyncObject`</ph> property to obtain an object to lock on.","pos":[20833,20927],"source":"Then when taking a lock, use the `InternalSyncObject` property to obtain an object to lock on."},{"content":"You do not need to use the property if you have initialized the internal synchronization object in your class constructor.","pos":[20929,21051]},{"content":"The double checking lock initialization code should look like this example:","pos":[21053,21128]},{"pos":[21726,21749],"content":"A Note About Lock(this)","linkify":"A Note About Lock(this)","nodes":[{"content":"A Note About Lock(this)","pos":[0,23]}]},{"content":"It is generally acceptable to take a lock on an individual object that is publicly accessible.","pos":[21753,21847]},{"content":"However, if the object is a singleton object that might cause an entire subsystem to deadlock, consider using the above design pattern as well.","pos":[21849,21992]},{"content":"For example, a lock on the one <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Security.SecurityManager&gt;</ph> object could cause a deadlock within the <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.AppDomain&gt;</ph> making the entire <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.AppDomain&gt;</ph> unusable.","pos":[21994,22180],"source":"  For example, a lock on the one <xref:System.Security.SecurityManager> object could cause a deadlock within the <xref:System.AppDomain> making the entire <xref:System.AppDomain> unusable."},{"content":"It is good practice to not take a lock on a publicly accessible object of this type.","pos":[22181,22265]},{"content":"However a lock on an individual collection or array should generally not present a problem.","pos":[22267,22358]},{"pos":[22369,22387],"content":"Code Analysis Rule","linkify":"Code Analysis Rule","nodes":[{"content":"Code Analysis Rule","pos":[0,18]}]},{"content":"Do not take locks on types that might be used across application domains or do not have a strong sense of identity.","pos":[22391,22506]},{"content":"Do not call <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Monitor.Enter%2A&gt;</ph> on a <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Type&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Reflection.MethodInfo&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph4\">&lt;xref:System.Reflection.PropertyInfo&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph5\">&lt;xref:System.String&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph6\">&lt;xref:System.ValueType&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph7\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Thread&gt;</ph>, or any object that derives from <ph id=\"ph8\">&lt;xref:System.MarshalByRefObject&gt;</ph>.","pos":[22507,22805],"source":" Do not call <xref:System.Threading.Monitor.Enter%2A> on a <xref:System.Type>, <xref:System.Reflection.MethodInfo>, <xref:System.Reflection.PropertyInfo>, <xref:System.String>, <xref:System.ValueType>, <xref:System.Threading.Thread>, or any object that derives from <xref:System.MarshalByRefObject>."},{"pos":[22815,22840],"content":"Remove GC.KeepAlive Calls","linkify":"Remove GC.KeepAlive Calls","nodes":[{"content":"Remove GC.KeepAlive Calls","pos":[0,25]}]},{"content":"A significant amount of existing code either does not use <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.GC.KeepAlive%2A&gt;</ph> when it should or uses it when it is not appropriate.","pos":[22844,22985],"source":"A significant amount of existing code either does not use <xref:System.GC.KeepAlive%2A> when it should or uses it when it is not appropriate."},{"content":"After converting to <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle&gt;</ph>, classes do not need to call <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.GC.KeepAlive%2A&gt;</ph>, assuming they do not have a finalizer but rely on <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle&gt;</ph> to finalize the operating system handles.","pos":[22987,23256],"source":"  After converting to <xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle>, classes do not need to call <xref:System.GC.KeepAlive%2A>, assuming they do not have a finalizer but rely on <xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle> to finalize the operating system handles."},{"content":"While the performance cost of retaining a call to <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.GC.KeepAlive%2A&gt;</ph> may be negligible, the perception that a call to <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.GC.KeepAlive%2A&gt;</ph> is either necessary or sufficient to solve a lifetime issue that may no longer exist makes the code more difficult to maintain.","pos":[23258,23544],"source":"  While the performance cost of retaining a call to <xref:System.GC.KeepAlive%2A> may be negligible, the perception that a call to <xref:System.GC.KeepAlive%2A> is either necessary or sufficient to solve a lifetime issue that may no longer exist makes the code more difficult to maintain."},{"content":"However, when using the COM interop CLR callable wrappers (RCWs), <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.GC.KeepAlive%2A&gt;</ph> is still required by code.","pos":[23546,23668],"source":"  However, when using the COM interop CLR callable wrappers (RCWs), <xref:System.GC.KeepAlive%2A> is still required by code."},{"pos":[23679,23697],"content":"Code Analysis Rule","linkify":"Code Analysis Rule","nodes":[{"content":"Code Analysis Rule","pos":[0,18]}]},{"content":"Remove <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.GC.KeepAlive%2A&gt;</ph>.","pos":[23701,23738],"source":"Remove <xref:System.GC.KeepAlive%2A>."},{"pos":[23748,23781],"content":"Use the Host Protection Attribute","linkify":"Use the Host Protection Attribute","nodes":[{"content":"Use the Host Protection Attribute","pos":[0,33]}]},{"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionAttribute&gt;</ph> (HPA) provides the use of declarative security actions to determine host protection requirements, allowing the host to prevent even fully trusted code from calling certain methods which are inappropriate for the given host, such as <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Environment.Exit%2A&gt;</ph> or <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.MessageBox.Show%2A&gt;</ph> for SQL Server.","pos":[23785,24179],"source":"The <xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionAttribute> (HPA) provides the use of declarative security actions to determine host protection requirements, allowing the host to prevent even fully trusted code from calling certain methods which are inappropriate for the given host, such as <xref:System.Environment.Exit%2A> or <xref:System.Windows.Forms.MessageBox.Show%2A> for SQL Server."},{"content":"The HPA affects only unmanaged applications that host the common language runtime and implement host protection, such as SQL Server.","pos":[24186,24318]},{"content":"When applied, the security action results in the creation of a link demand based on the host resources the class or method exposes.","pos":[24319,24450]},{"content":"If the code is run in a client application or on a server that is not host-protected, the attribute \"evaporates\"; it is not detected and therefore not applied.","pos":[24451,24610]},{"pos":[24618,24929],"content":"[!IMPORTANT]\n The purpose of this attribute is to enforce host-specific programming model guidelines, not security behavior.  Although a link demand is used to check for conformance to programming model requirements, the <xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionAttribute> is not a security permission.","leadings":["","> "],"nodes":[{"content":"The purpose of this attribute is to enforce host-specific programming model guidelines, not security behavior.  Although a link demand is used to check for conformance to programming model requirements, the <xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionAttribute> is not a security permission.","pos":[14,309],"nodes":[{"content":"The purpose of this attribute is to enforce host-specific programming model guidelines, not security behavior.","pos":[0,110]},{"content":"Although a link demand is used to check for conformance to programming model requirements, the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionAttribute&gt;</ph> is not a security permission.","pos":[112,295],"source":"  Although a link demand is used to check for conformance to programming model requirements, the <xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionAttribute> is not a security permission."}]}]},{"content":"If the host does not have programming model requirements, the link demands do not occur.","pos":[24936,25024]},{"content":"This attribute identifies the following:","pos":[25031,25071]},{"content":"Methods or classes that do not fit the host programming model, but are otherwise benign.","pos":[25081,25169]},{"content":"Methods or classes that do not fit the host programming model and could lead to destabilizing server-managed user code.","pos":[25179,25298]},{"content":"Methods or classes that do not fit the host programming model and could lead to a destabilization of the server process itself.","pos":[25308,25435]},{"pos":[25443,25907],"content":"[!NOTE]\n If you are creating a class library that is to be called by applications that may execute in a host protected environment, you should apply this attribute to members that expose <xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionResource> resource categories. The .NET Framework class library members with this attribute cause only the immediate caller to be checked.  Your library member must also cause a check of its immediate caller in the same manner.","leadings":["","> "],"nodes":[{"content":"If you are creating a class library that is to be called by applications that may execute in a host protected environment, you should apply this attribute to members that expose <xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionResource> resource categories. The .NET Framework class library members with this attribute cause only the immediate caller to be checked.  Your library member must also cause a check of its immediate caller in the same manner.","pos":[9,462],"nodes":[{"content":"If you are creating a class library that is to be called by applications that may execute in a host protected environment, you should apply this attribute to members that expose <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionResource&gt;</ph> resource categories.","pos":[0,256],"source":"If you are creating a class library that is to be called by applications that may execute in a host protected environment, you should apply this attribute to members that expose <xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionResource> resource categories."},{"content":"The .NET Framework class library members with this attribute cause only the immediate caller to be checked.","pos":[257,364]},{"content":"Your library member must also cause a check of its immediate caller in the same manner.","pos":[366,453]}]}]},{"content":"Please find more information on HPA in <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionAttribute&gt;</ph>.","pos":[25914,26012],"source":"Please find more information on HPA in <xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionAttribute>."},{"pos":[26023,26041],"content":"Code Analysis Rule","linkify":"Code Analysis Rule","nodes":[{"content":"Code Analysis Rule","pos":[0,18]}]},{"content":"For SQL Server, all methods used to introduce synchronization or threading must identified with the HPA.","pos":[26045,26149]},{"content":"This includes methods that share state, are synchronized, or manage external processes.","pos":[26150,26237]},{"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionResource&gt;</ph> values that impact SQL Server are <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionResource&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionResource&gt;</ph>, and <ph id=\"ph4\">&lt;xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionResource&gt;</ph>.","pos":[26238,26514],"source":" The <xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionResource> values that impact SQL Server are <xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionResource>, <xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionResource>, and <xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionResource>."},{"content":"However, any method that exposes any <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionResource&gt;</ph> should be identified by a HPA, not just those using resources affecting SQL.","pos":[26515,26686],"source":" However, any method that exposes any <xref:System.Security.Permissions.HostProtectionResource> should be identified by a HPA, not just those using resources affecting SQL."},{"pos":[26696,26739],"content":"Do Not Block Indefinitely in Unmanaged Code","linkify":"Do Not Block Indefinitely in Unmanaged Code","nodes":[{"content":"Do Not Block Indefinitely in Unmanaged Code","pos":[0,43]}]},{"content":"Blocking in unmanaged code instead of in managed code can cause a denial of service attack because the CLR is not able to abort the thread.","pos":[26743,26882]},{"content":"A blocked thread prevents the CLR from unloading the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.AppDomain&gt;</ph>, at least without doing some extremely unsafe operations.","pos":[26884,27018],"source":"  A blocked thread prevents the CLR from unloading the <xref:System.AppDomain>, at least without doing some extremely unsafe operations."},{"content":"Blocking using a Win32 synchronization primitive is a clear example of something we cannot allow.","pos":[27020,27117]},{"content":"Blocking in a call to <ph id=\"ph1\">`ReadFile`</ph> on a socket should be avoided if possible — ideally the Win32 API should provide a mechanism for an operation like this to time out.","pos":[27119,27284],"source":"  Blocking in a call to `ReadFile` on a socket should be avoided if possible — ideally the Win32 API should provide a mechanism for an operation like this to time out."},{"content":"Any method that calls into native should ideally use a Win32 call with a reasonable, finite timeout.","pos":[27291,27391]},{"content":"If the user is allowed to specify the timeout, the user should not be allowed to specify an infinite timeout without some specific security permission.","pos":[27393,27544]},{"content":"As a guideline, if a method will block for more than ~10 seconds, you need to be using a version that supports timeouts or you need additional CLR support.","pos":[27546,27701]},{"content":"Here are some examples of problematic API’s.","pos":[27708,27752]},{"content":"Pipes (both anonymous and named) can be created with a timeout; however, code must ensure it never calls <ph id=\"ph1\">`CreateNamedPipe`</ph> nor <ph id=\"ph2\">`WaitNamedPipe`</ph> with NMPWAIT_WAIT_FOREVER.","pos":[27754,27923],"source":"  Pipes (both anonymous and named) can be created with a timeout; however, code must ensure it never calls `CreateNamedPipe` nor `WaitNamedPipe` with NMPWAIT_WAIT_FOREVER."},{"content":"Additionally, there can be unexpected blocking even if a timeout is specified.","pos":[27925,28003]},{"content":"Calling <ph id=\"ph1\">`WriteFile`</ph> on an anonymous pipe will block until all bytes are written, meaning if the buffer has unread data in it, the <ph id=\"ph2\">`WriteFile`</ph> call will block until the reader has freed up space in the pipe’s buffer.","pos":[28005,28220],"source":"  Calling `WriteFile` on an anonymous pipe will block until all bytes are written, meaning if the buffer has unread data in it, the `WriteFile` call will block until the reader has freed up space in the pipe’s buffer."},{"content":"Sockets should always use some API that honors a timeout mechanism.","pos":[28222,28289]},{"pos":[28300,28318],"content":"Code Analysis Rule","linkify":"Code Analysis Rule","nodes":[{"content":"Code Analysis Rule","pos":[0,18]}]},{"content":"Blocking without a timeout in unmanaged code is a denial of service attack.","pos":[28322,28397]},{"content":"Do not perform platform invoke calls to <ph id=\"ph1\">`WaitForSingleObject`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph2\">`WaitForSingleObjectEx`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph3\">`WaitForMultipleObjects`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph4\">`MsgWaitForMultipleObjects`</ph>, and <ph id=\"ph5\">`MsgWaitForMultipleObjectsEx`</ph>.","pos":[28398,28575],"source":" Do not perform platform invoke calls to `WaitForSingleObject`, `WaitForSingleObjectEx`, `WaitForMultipleObjects`, `MsgWaitForMultipleObjects`, and `MsgWaitForMultipleObjectsEx`."},{"content":"Do not use NMPWAIT_WAIT_FOREVER.","pos":[28577,28609]},{"pos":[28619,28655],"content":"Identify Any STA-Dependent Features.","linkify":"Identify Any STA-Dependent Features.","nodes":[{"content":"Identify Any STA-Dependent Features.","pos":[0,36]}]},{"content":"Identify any code that uses COM single-threaded apartments (STAs).","pos":[28659,28725]},{"content":"STAs are disabled in the SQL Server process.","pos":[28727,28771]},{"content":"Features that depend on <ph id=\"ph1\">`CoInitialize`</ph>, such as performance counters or the clipboard, must be disabled within SQL Server.","pos":[28773,28895],"source":"  Features that depend on `CoInitialize`, such as performance counters or the clipboard, must be disabled within SQL Server."},{"pos":[28905,28959],"content":"Ensure Finalizers Are Free of Synchronization Problems","linkify":"Ensure Finalizers Are Free of Synchronization Problems","nodes":[{"content":"Ensure Finalizers Are Free of Synchronization Problems","pos":[0,54]}]},{"content":"Multiple finalizer threads might exist in future versions of the .NET Framework, meaning the finalizers for different instances of the same type run simultaneously.","pos":[28963,29127]},{"content":"They do not have to be completely thread safe; the garbage collector guarantees that only one thread will run the finalizer for a given object instance.","pos":[29129,29281]},{"content":"However, the finalizers must be coded to avoid race conditions and deadlocks when running simultaneously on multiple different object instances.","pos":[29283,29427]},{"content":"When using any external state, such as writing to a log file, in a finalizer, threading issues must be handled.","pos":[29429,29540]},{"content":"Do not rely on finalization to provide thread safety.","pos":[29542,29595]},{"content":"Do not use thread local storage, managed or native, to store state on the finalizer thread.","pos":[29596,29687]},{"pos":[29698,29716],"content":"Code Analysis Rule","linkify":"Code Analysis Rule","nodes":[{"content":"Code Analysis Rule","pos":[0,18]}]},{"content":"Finalizers must be free of synchronization problems.","pos":[29720,29772]},{"content":"Do not use a static mutable state in a finalizer.","pos":[29773,29822]},{"pos":[29832,29866],"content":"Avoid Unmanaged Memory If Possible","linkify":"Avoid Unmanaged Memory If Possible","nodes":[{"content":"Avoid Unmanaged Memory If Possible","pos":[0,34]}]},{"content":"Unmanaged memory can be leaked, just like an operating system handle.","pos":[29870,29939]},{"content":"If possible, try to use memory on the stack using <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>stackalloc<ept id=\"p1\">](~/docs/csharp/language-reference/keywords/stackalloc.md)</ept> or a pinned managed object such as the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>fixed Statement<ept id=\"p2\">](~/docs/csharp/language-reference/keywords/fixed-statement.md)</ept> or a <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.GCHandle&gt;</ph> using a byte[].","pos":[29941,30247],"source":"  If possible, try to use memory on the stack using [stackalloc](~/docs/csharp/language-reference/keywords/stackalloc.md) or a pinned managed object such as the [fixed Statement](~/docs/csharp/language-reference/keywords/fixed-statement.md) or a <xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.GCHandle> using a byte[]."},{"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.GC&gt;</ph> eventually cleans these up.","pos":[30249,30297],"source":"  The <xref:System.GC> eventually cleans these up."},{"content":"However, if you must allocate unmanaged memory, consider using a class that derives from <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle&gt;</ph> to wrap the memory allocation.","pos":[30299,30467],"source":"  However, if you must allocate unmanaged memory, consider using a class that derives from <xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle> to wrap the memory allocation."},{"content":"Note that there is at least one case where <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle&gt;</ph> is not adequate.","pos":[30474,30582],"source":"Note that there is at least one case where <xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle> is not adequate."},{"content":"For COM method calls that allocate or free memory, it is common for one DLL to allocate memory via <ph id=\"ph1\">`CoTaskMemAlloc`</ph> then another DLL frees that memory with <ph id=\"ph2\">`CoTaskMemFree`</ph>.","pos":[30584,30756],"source":"  For COM method calls that allocate or free memory, it is common for one DLL to allocate memory via `CoTaskMemAlloc` then another DLL frees that memory with `CoTaskMemFree`."},{"content":"Using <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle&gt;</ph> in these places would be inappropriate since it will attempt to tie the lifetime of the unmanaged memory to the lifetime of the <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle&gt;</ph> instead of allowing the other DLL control the lifetime of the memory.","pos":[30758,31059],"source":"  Using <xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle> in these places would be inappropriate since it will attempt to tie the lifetime of the unmanaged memory to the lifetime of the <xref:System.Runtime.InteropServices.SafeHandle> instead of allowing the other DLL control the lifetime of the memory."},{"pos":[31069,31104],"content":"Review All Uses of Catch(Exception)","linkify":"Review All Uses of Catch(Exception)","nodes":[{"content":"Review All Uses of Catch(Exception)","pos":[0,35]}]},{"content":"Catch blocks that catch all exceptions instead of one specific exception will now catch the asynchronous exceptions as well.","pos":[31108,31232]},{"content":"Examine every catch(Exception) block, looking for no important resource releasing or backout code that might be skipped, as well as potentially incorrect behavior within the catch block itself for handling a <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.ThreadAbortException&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.StackOverflowException&gt;</ph>, or <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.OutOfMemoryException&gt;</ph>.","pos":[31234,31564],"source":"  Examine every catch(Exception) block, looking for no important resource releasing or backout code that might be skipped, as well as potentially incorrect behavior within the catch block itself for handling a <xref:System.Threading.ThreadAbortException>, <xref:System.StackOverflowException>, or <xref:System.OutOfMemoryException>."},{"content":"Note that it is possible this code might be logging or making some assumptions that it may only see certain exceptions, or that whenever an exception happens it failed for exactly one particular reason.","pos":[31566,31768]},{"content":"These assumptions may need to be updated to include <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.ThreadAbortException&gt;</ph>.","pos":[31770,31867],"source":"  These assumptions may need to be updated to include <xref:System.Threading.ThreadAbortException>."},{"content":"Consider changing all places that catch all exceptions to catching a specific type of exception that you expect will be thrown, such as a <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.FormatException&gt;</ph> from string formatting methods.","pos":[31874,32073],"source":"Consider changing all places that catch all exceptions to catching a specific type of exception that you expect will be thrown, such as a <xref:System.FormatException> from string formatting methods."},{"content":"This prevents the catch block from running on unexpected exceptions and will help ensure the code does not hide bugs by catching unexpected exceptions.","pos":[32075,32226]},{"content":"As a general rule never handle an exception in library code (code that requires you to catch an exception may indicate a design flaw in the code you are calling).","pos":[32228,32390]},{"content":"In some cases you may want to catch an exception and throw a different exception type to provide more data.","pos":[32392,32499]},{"content":"Use nested exceptions in this case, storing the real cause of the failure in the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Exception.InnerException%2A&gt;</ph> property of the new exception.","pos":[32501,32654],"source":"  Use nested exceptions in this case, storing the real cause of the failure in the <xref:System.Exception.InnerException%2A> property of the new exception."},{"pos":[32665,32683],"content":"Code Analysis Rule","linkify":"Code Analysis Rule","nodes":[{"content":"Code Analysis Rule","pos":[0,18]}]},{"content":"Review all catch blocks in managed code that catch all objects or catch all exceptions.","pos":[32687,32774]},{"content":"In C#, this means flagging both <ph id=\"ph1\">`catch`</ph> {} and <ph id=\"ph2\">`catch(Exception)`</ph> {}.","pos":[32776,32845],"source":"  In C#, this means flagging both `catch` {} and `catch(Exception)` {}."},{"content":"Consider making the exception type very specific, or review the code to ensure it does not act in a bad way if it catches an unexpected exception type.","pos":[32847,32998]},{"pos":[33008,33072],"content":"Do Not Assume a Managed Thread Is a Win32 Thread – It Is a Fiber","linkify":"Do Not Assume a Managed Thread Is a Win32 Thread – It Is a Fiber","nodes":[{"content":"Do Not Assume a Managed Thread Is a Win32 Thread – It Is a Fiber","pos":[0,64]}]},{"content":"Using managed thread local storage does work, but you may not use unmanaged thread local storage or assume the code will run on the current operating system thread again.","pos":[33076,33246]},{"content":"Do not change settings like the thread’s locale.","pos":[33248,33296]},{"content":"Do not call <ph id=\"ph1\">`InitializeCriticalSection`</ph> or <ph id=\"ph2\">`CreateMutex`</ph> via platform invoke because they require the operating system thread that enters a lock also exit the lock.","pos":[33298,33462],"source":"  Do not call `InitializeCriticalSection` or `CreateMutex` via platform invoke because they require the operating system thread that enters a lock also exit the lock."},{"content":"Since this will not be the case when using fibers, Win32 critical sections and mutexes cannot be used in SQL directly.","pos":[33464,33582]},{"content":"Note that the managed <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Mutex&gt;</ph> class does not handle these thread affinity concerns.","pos":[33584,33689],"source":"  Note that the managed <xref:System.Threading.Mutex> class does not handle these thread affinity concerns."},{"content":"You can safely use most of the state on a managed <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Thread&gt;</ph> object, including managed thread local storage and the thread’s current UI culture.","pos":[33696,33860],"source":"You can safely use most of the state on a managed <xref:System.Threading.Thread> object, including managed thread local storage and the thread’s current UI culture."},{"content":"You can also use the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.ThreadStaticAttribute&gt;</ph>, which makes the value of an existing static variable accessible only by the current managed thread (this is another way of doing fiber local storage in the CLR).","pos":[33862,34081],"source":"  You can also use the <xref:System.ThreadStaticAttribute>, which makes the value of an existing static variable accessible only by the current managed thread (this is another way of doing fiber local storage in the CLR)."},{"content":"For programming model reasons, you can not change the current culture of a thread when running in SQL.","pos":[34083,34185]},{"pos":[34196,34214],"content":"Code Analysis Rule","linkify":"Code Analysis Rule","nodes":[{"content":"Code Analysis Rule","pos":[0,18]}]},{"content":"SQL Server runs in fiber mode; do not use thread local storage.","pos":[34218,34281]},{"content":"Avoid platform invoke calls to <ph id=\"ph1\">`TlsAlloc`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph2\">`TlsFree`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph3\">`TlsGetValue`</ph>, and <ph id=\"ph4\">`TlsSetValue.`</ph>","pos":[34282,34369],"source":" Avoid platform invoke calls to `TlsAlloc`, `TlsFree`, `TlsGetValue`, and `TlsSetValue.`"},{"pos":[34379,34414],"content":"Let SQL Server Handle Impersonation","linkify":"Let SQL Server Handle Impersonation","nodes":[{"content":"Let SQL Server Handle Impersonation","pos":[0,35]}]},{"pos":[34418,34576],"content":"Since impersonation operates on the thread level and SQL can run in fiber mode, managed code should not impersonate users, and should not call <ph id=\"ph1\">`RevertToSelf`</ph>.","source":"Since impersonation operates on the thread level and SQL can run in fiber mode, managed code should not impersonate users, and should not call `RevertToSelf`."},{"pos":[34587,34605],"content":"Code Analysis Rule","linkify":"Code Analysis Rule","nodes":[{"content":"Code Analysis Rule","pos":[0,18]}]},{"content":"Let SQL Server handle impersonation.","pos":[34609,34645]},{"content":"Do not use <ph id=\"ph1\">`RevertToSelf`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph2\">`ImpersonateAnonymousToken`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph3\">`DdeImpersonateClient`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph4\">`ImpersonateDdeClientWindow`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph5\">`ImpersonateLoggedOnUser`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph6\">`ImpersonateNamedPipeClient`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph7\">`ImpersonateSelf`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph8\">`RpcImpersonateClient`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph9\">`RpcRevertToSelf`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph10\">`RpcRevertToSelfEx`</ph>, or <ph id=\"ph11\">`SetThreadToken`</ph>.","pos":[34646,34916],"source":" Do not use `RevertToSelf`, `ImpersonateAnonymousToken`, `DdeImpersonateClient`, `ImpersonateDdeClientWindow`, `ImpersonateLoggedOnUser`, `ImpersonateNamedPipeClient`, `ImpersonateSelf`, `RpcImpersonateClient`, `RpcRevertToSelf`, `RpcRevertToSelfEx`, or `SetThreadToken`."},{"pos":[34926,34953],"content":"Do Not Call Thread::Suspend","linkify":"Do Not Call Thread::Suspend","nodes":[{"content":"Do Not Call Thread::Suspend","pos":[0,27]}]},{"content":"The ability to suspend a thread may appear a simple operation, but it can cause deadlocks.","pos":[34957,35047]},{"content":"If a thread holding a lock gets suspended by a second thread and then the second thread tries taking the same lock, a deadlock occurs.","pos":[35049,35183]},{"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Thread.Suspend%2A&gt;</ph> can interfere with security, class loading, remoting, and reflection currently.","pos":[35185,35306],"source":"  <xref:System.Threading.Thread.Suspend%2A> can interfere with security, class loading, remoting, and reflection currently."},{"pos":[35317,35335],"content":"Code Analysis Rule","linkify":"Code Analysis Rule","nodes":[{"content":"Code Analysis Rule","pos":[0,18]}]},{"content":"Do not call <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Thread.Suspend%2A&gt;</ph>.","pos":[35339,35393],"source":"Do not call <xref:System.Threading.Thread.Suspend%2A>."},{"content":"Consider using a real synchronization primitive instead, such as a <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Semaphore&gt;</ph> or <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.ManualResetEvent&gt;</ph> .","pos":[35394,35540],"source":" Consider using a real synchronization primitive instead, such as a <xref:System.Threading.Semaphore> or <xref:System.Threading.ManualResetEvent> ."},{"pos":[35550,35638],"content":"Protect Critical Operations with Constrained Execution Regions and Reliability Contracts","linkify":"Protect Critical Operations with Constrained Execution Regions and Reliability Contracts","nodes":[{"content":"Protect Critical Operations with Constrained Execution Regions and Reliability Contracts","pos":[0,88]}]},{"content":"When performing a complex operation that updates a shared status or that needs to deterministically either fully succeed or fully fail, be sure that it is protected by a constrained execution region (CER).","pos":[35642,35847]},{"content":"This guarantees that the code runs in every case, even an abrupt thread abort or an abrupt <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.AppDomain&gt;</ph> unload.","pos":[35848,35970],"source":" This guarantees that the code runs in every case, even an abrupt thread abort or an abrupt <xref:System.AppDomain> unload."},{"pos":[35977,36136],"content":"A CER is a particular <ph id=\"ph1\">`try/finally`</ph> block immediately preceded by a call to <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Runtime.CompilerServices.RuntimeHelpers.PrepareConstrainedRegions%2A&gt;</ph>.","source":"A CER is a particular `try/finally` block immediately preceded by a call to <xref:System.Runtime.CompilerServices.RuntimeHelpers.PrepareConstrainedRegions%2A>."},{"content":"Doing so instructs the just-in-time compiler to prepare all the code in the finally block before running the <ph id=\"ph1\">`try`</ph> block.","pos":[36143,36264],"source":"Doing so instructs the just-in-time compiler to prepare all the code in the finally block before running the `try` block."},{"content":"This guarantees that the code in the finally block is built and will run in all cases.","pos":[36265,36351]},{"content":"It is not uncommon in a CER to have an empty <ph id=\"ph1\">`try`</ph> block.","pos":[36352,36409],"source":" It is not uncommon in a CER to have an empty `try` block."},{"content":"Using a CER protects against asynchronous thread aborts and out-of-memory exceptions.","pos":[36410,36495]},{"content":"See <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Runtime.CompilerServices.RuntimeHelpers.ExecuteCodeWithGuaranteedCleanup%2A&gt;</ph> for a form of a CER that additionally handles stack overflows for exceedingly deep code.","pos":[36496,36678],"source":" See <xref:System.Runtime.CompilerServices.RuntimeHelpers.ExecuteCodeWithGuaranteedCleanup%2A> for a form of a CER that additionally handles stack overflows for exceedingly deep code."},{"pos":[36687,36695],"content":"See Also","linkify":"See Also","nodes":[{"content":"See Also","pos":[0,8]}]},{"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Runtime.ConstrainedExecution&gt;</ph>","pos":[36699,36741],"source":"<xref:System.Runtime.ConstrainedExecution> "},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>SQL Server Programming and Host Protection Attributes<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../docs/framework/performance/sql-server-programming-and-host-protection-attributes.md)</ept>","pos":[36746,36895],"source":"[SQL Server Programming and Host Protection Attributes](../../../docs/framework/performance/sql-server-programming-and-host-protection-attributes.md)"}]}